theorem
Th1: ((((a is  convergent & b is  convergent) & ( lim a ) = ( lim b )) & (for n holds (( d . ( 2 * n ) ) = ( a . n ) & ( d . ( ( 2 * n ) + 1 ) ) = ( b . n )))) implies (d is  convergent & ( lim d ) = ( lim a )))
proof
assume that
A1: a is  convergent
and
A2: b is  convergent
and
A3: ( lim a ) = ( lim b )
and
A4: (for n holds (( d . ( 2 * n ) ) = ( a . n ) & ( d . ( ( 2 * n ) + 1 ) ) = ( b . n )));
A5:now
let r being  real number;
assume A6: ( 0 ) < r;
then consider k1 being (Element of ( NAT )) such that A7: (for m holds (k1 <= m implies ( abs ( ( a . m ) - ( lim a ) ) ) < r)) by A1,SEQ_2:def 7;
consider k2 being (Element of ( NAT )) such that A8: (for m holds (k2 <= m implies ( abs ( ( b . m ) - ( lim b ) ) ) < r)) by A2,A6,SEQ_2:def 7;
take n = ( max (( 2 * k1 ),( ( 2 * k2 ) + 1 )) );
let m;
assume A9: n <= m;
then A10: ( ( 2 * k2 ) + 1 ) <= m by XXREAL_0:30;
consider n such that A11: (m = ( 2 * n ) or m = ( ( 2 * n ) + 1 )) by SCHEME1:1;
A12: ( 2 * k1 ) <= m by A9,XXREAL_0:30;
now
per cases  by A11;
suppose A13: m = ( 2 * n );

then A14: n >= k1 by A12,XREAL_1:68;
( abs ( ( d . m ) - ( lim a ) ) ) = ( abs ( ( a . n ) - ( lim a ) ) ) by A4,A13;
hence ( abs ( ( d . m ) - ( lim a ) ) ) < r by A7,A14;
end;
suppose A15: m = ( ( 2 * n ) + 1 );

A16:now
assume n < k2;
then ( 2 * n ) < ( 2 * k2 ) by XREAL_1:68;
hence contradiction by A10,A15,XREAL_1:6;
end;
( abs ( ( d . m ) - ( lim a ) ) ) = ( abs ( ( b . n ) - ( lim a ) ) ) by A4,A15;
hence ( abs ( ( d . m ) - ( lim a ) ) ) < r by A3,A8,A16;
end;
end;
hence ( abs ( ( d . m ) - ( lim a ) ) ) < r;
end;
hence d is  convergent by SEQ_2:def 6;
hence thesis by A5,SEQ_2:def 7;
end;
